WEBVTT

00:08.200 --> 00:12.520
[cheering]

00:12.600 --> 00:14.280
It's nice to be happy.

00:14.360 --> 00:15.360
[laughter]

00:15.440 --> 00:17.360
The world's awful at the minute, isn't it?

00:17.440 --> 00:19.240
How depressing is the world?

00:19.320 --> 00:22.040
Look at politics in this country.
The right are too right,

00:22.120 --> 00:24.480
and the left are too left.
None of them speak for us.

00:24.560 --> 00:27.320
It's ridiculous. "Brexit means Brexit."

00:27.400 --> 00:29.440
"I want my country back!"

00:29.520 --> 00:31.240
And over here it's just as bad.

00:31.320 --> 00:34.200
"What are we going
to call female fishermen?"

00:34.280 --> 00:35.640
[laughter]

00:37.400 --> 00:40.200
It's not your country. "Vaganglers."

00:40.280 --> 00:41.480
Can we not?

00:41.560 --> 00:42.760
[laughter]

00:42.840 --> 00:44.960
[applause]

00:45.040 --> 00:47.040
Discuss something that matters!

00:50.920 --> 00:52.120
Oh God.

00:53.120 --> 00:54.040
Greetings.

00:56.600 --> 01:00.360
This feels like the scene
where the murderer confesses.

01:01.480 --> 01:04.120
I haven't killed anyone, but I do have now

01:04.200 --> 01:06.880
the same amount of
Netflix specials as Ted Bundy.

01:07.760 --> 01:11.200
Have you seen the latest
social media trend?  Rib cage bragging,

01:11.280 --> 01:14.600
where supermodels lean back,
and they brag about their ribs.

01:14.680 --> 01:17.240
Now, I can't speak for women.
I can speak for every man

01:17.320 --> 01:20.800
who has ever walked the Earth.
No man has ever looked at a lady and gone,

01:20.880 --> 01:24.560
"Fucking look at the ribs on that!"

01:24.640 --> 01:25.680
[laughter]

01:25.760 --> 01:29.120
'Cause we're looking at you as women!
Not percussion instruments!

01:29.960 --> 01:32.240
We're not going to get in there and go…
[purring] "Oh yeah!"

01:32.320 --> 01:34.080
[purring] "Oh yeah!"

01:34.160 --> 01:35.120
[purring]

01:35.200 --> 01:37.920
[cheering and applause]

01:38.000 --> 01:40.800
[man] What was this documentary
supposed to be about?

01:40.880 --> 01:43.680
It was supposed to be about me

01:43.760 --> 01:45.520
doing a big world tour.

01:46.160 --> 01:48.080
Having done stand-up for 20 years.

01:48.960 --> 01:50.160
Just got married,

01:50.960 --> 01:52.080
was turning 40,

01:52.720 --> 01:53.800
and…

01:55.680 --> 01:57.200
Yeah. What was it about?

02:00.800 --> 02:03.560
[rock music playing]

02:22.480 --> 02:24.800
[announcer] Russell Howard!

02:24.880 --> 02:28.080
[rock music continues]

02:29.560 --> 02:30.720
There's that, "Yes!"

02:30.800 --> 02:33.320
The sort of elation as to why
you do it in the first place.

02:33.400 --> 02:35.600
[Russell yelling]

02:35.680 --> 02:37.680
You've beat both
Frank Sinatra and Barry Manilow

02:37.760 --> 02:40.400
for the record of the most
consecutive nights performed

02:40.480 --> 02:42.080
at the Royal Albert Hall.

02:42.160 --> 02:45.720
At the minute, I'm just a fucking machine
that is trying to create.

02:53.520 --> 02:57.600
I feel so out of touch
with everybody at the moment.

03:04.120 --> 03:06.680
Thank you from
the bottom of my heart for coming.

03:06.760 --> 03:09.560
A normal man like me shouldn't have fun…

03:11.040 --> 03:15.600
So that's what
it was meant to be about, but then

03:16.720 --> 03:18.320
bats got involved.

03:18.400 --> 03:20.440
In the past two weeks,

03:20.520 --> 03:24.280
the number of cases
of COVID-19 outside China

03:24.360 --> 03:26.800
has increased 13-fold.

03:26.880 --> 03:27.920
Good evening.

03:28.640 --> 03:33.480
The coronavirus is the biggest threat
this country has faced for decades.

03:33.560 --> 03:37.520
From this evening, I must give
the British people a simple instruction.

03:38.160 --> 03:40.120
You must stay at home.

03:40.200 --> 03:42.480
So my wife's a doctor

03:42.560 --> 03:46.600
and she planned
her first-ever career break.

03:46.680 --> 03:50.200
She was going to
come on tour with me to Europe,

03:50.280 --> 03:52.240
and America, and Australia.

03:52.320 --> 03:56.320
We'd even hired
Dolly Parton's tour van for a bit of it.

03:57.880 --> 04:00.800
But when COVID hit, my wife said,

04:01.560 --> 04:03.080
"I'm going to go back to work."

04:03.160 --> 04:07.040
"You're gonna stay with your parents,
'cause we don't know how bad it will be."

04:07.120 --> 04:11.400
"And then when it gets better,
you can come back."

04:11.920 --> 04:14.080
I finished my TV show

04:14.160 --> 04:19.040
on February 25th.

04:19.120 --> 04:20.240
That was the last show.

04:20.320 --> 04:21.840
-[cheering and applause]
-Hello!

04:22.360 --> 04:27.240
Thanks very much for watching the series!
We'll be back in autumn! Good night!

04:27.320 --> 04:29.800
Have a wonderful year! Farewell!

04:31.320 --> 04:36.720
I was doing shows
in Scandinavia, and Germany, and Holland.

04:37.680 --> 04:41.840
And Budapest, and Vienna, and Helsinki.

04:42.360 --> 04:46.040
Then I was doing a tour of America in May.

04:46.120 --> 04:48.240
Then July, I was going to Australia.

04:48.320 --> 04:51.760
Then in September,
I was going to Hammersmith in London.

04:51.840 --> 04:53.800
I was gonna record
the special for Netflix.

04:53.880 --> 04:56.400
That's the diary.
That's how it was all set out.

04:56.960 --> 04:58.520
Lovely like that.

04:58.600 --> 04:59.720
And that's all gone.

05:04.840 --> 05:07.320
I love my family,
but if you had told me in

05:08.080 --> 05:11.600
April 2019 that in a year's time,

05:11.680 --> 05:16.360
you'll be staying
with your parents as a 40-year-old man,

05:16.440 --> 05:18.640
sleeping in your childhood bed,

05:18.720 --> 05:21.240
and you won't be
allowed to leave the house…

05:24.080 --> 05:25.160
I'd be confused.

05:28.600 --> 05:31.520
I've learned that
my mom pretty much lives to embarrass me.

05:31.600 --> 05:33.520
-[woman whoops]
-We were in a car, on a motorway,

05:33.600 --> 05:34.520
stuck in traffic.

05:34.600 --> 05:38.000
This bloke got out of his car,
knocked on our window, and,

05:38.080 --> 05:39.200
"Can I have your photo?"

05:39.280 --> 05:41.360
-[laughter]
-That's fairly weird.

05:41.440 --> 05:45.920
It's made even weirder
when your mom goes, "Help!"

05:46.000 --> 05:48.080
[laughter]

05:48.160 --> 05:50.440
"He's kidnapped me!"

05:57.560 --> 05:58.880
Why are you wearing makeup?

05:58.960 --> 06:01.480
It's not that you knew
there was a camera coming?

06:01.560 --> 06:02.560
No, I didn't know!

06:02.640 --> 06:05.800
-Is he wearing mascara?
-Why don't you shave that tidy?

06:05.880 --> 06:07.080
I would ask the same of you.

06:07.160 --> 06:08.400
[Ninette giggling]

06:08.480 --> 06:10.920
[Russell]
My mom loves the fact that I do stand-up.

06:11.000 --> 06:14.360
She'll come to the same show
20 times in a row and still laugh.

06:14.440 --> 06:15.960
I'm like, "You've seen it."

06:17.240 --> 06:18.560
"Yeah, but I forget."

06:19.520 --> 06:21.040
[man] Does he like you putting them up?

06:21.120 --> 06:23.840
No, he didn't say,
"I want to put the pictures."

06:23.920 --> 06:25.240
He said, "I'm not a shrine."

06:26.320 --> 06:27.680
Should we put them out?

06:29.240 --> 06:31.240
I mean, they're wonderful.

06:36.040 --> 06:41.320
This is a painting I did of him years ago.
In my kitchen years ago.

06:42.320 --> 06:44.000
He hates it, of course.

06:44.080 --> 06:45.360
[Ninette giggling]

06:45.440 --> 06:47.440
I mean, it's just creepy, innit?

06:47.960 --> 06:49.320
Who paints their son?

06:51.400 --> 06:54.040
My relationship with my mom has changed.

06:54.120 --> 06:58.320
When I was young,
we used to watch TV together,

06:58.400 --> 07:00.640
because Dad was away working.

07:00.720 --> 07:04.560
So I would kind of…
I became her sort of husband.

07:05.520 --> 07:08.840
[Ninette] I remember, because he was
a little bit older than Daniel and Kerry,

07:08.920 --> 07:10.640
I would let him stay up later.

07:10.720 --> 07:13.160
He would make me a cup of tea.

07:13.240 --> 07:16.560
He would bring it in
on a tray and be so pleased

07:16.640 --> 07:20.080
that he had that special time
to be able to sit down.

07:20.160 --> 07:22.000
I think we watched Coronation Street.

07:22.080 --> 07:23.640
Something silly like that.

07:23.720 --> 07:26.200
But he could make me a cup of tea,

07:26.280 --> 07:28.960
and do that, and he liked that.

07:29.040 --> 07:31.600
Sometimes, I could push it
to nine o'clock.

07:31.680 --> 07:35.480
Then she'd suddenly come to
and realize I wasn't her husband.

07:35.560 --> 07:37.720
I was a child that needed to go to bed.

07:39.440 --> 07:41.400
I think Dad's got a job for you today.

07:41.960 --> 07:43.600
Good luck with that. I'm leaving in a bit.

07:43.680 --> 07:45.320
[Ninette giggling]

07:45.400 --> 07:47.120
Should we lift it like that?
That's easier.

07:47.200 --> 07:49.600
-How do you mean?
-As in, across like that?

07:49.680 --> 07:51.960
No, because we've got
to get up the stairs.

07:58.000 --> 08:02.080
[Russell] I'm funny because of my mom,
and I'm determined because of my dad.

08:02.600 --> 08:04.280
The thing is, I love my dad.

08:04.960 --> 08:08.520
I think he… And I really respect him.

08:08.600 --> 08:12.280
Nobody has drive like my dad, nobody.

08:12.920 --> 08:16.080
My career has had a big impact
on my relationship with my dad

08:16.160 --> 08:20.360
because I think my dad…
I was going to say I think he respects me.

08:20.440 --> 08:21.480
I don't think he does.

08:21.560 --> 08:23.720
I always tell him after every gig,

08:24.240 --> 08:26.400
in a completely sincere way,

08:27.000 --> 08:28.800
that he's brilliant.

08:28.880 --> 08:32.080
I might not use
those words, but it will be

08:32.720 --> 08:35.320
flavors of excellent, fantastic.

08:35.400 --> 08:38.000
So he's had plenty of cues.

08:38.080 --> 08:41.080
If that's still in his head,
then he needs to talk to somebody.

08:41.160 --> 08:43.520
That's his own demons then, isn't it?

08:43.600 --> 08:45.760
What about moving the stuff in the shed?

08:45.840 --> 08:46.720
Leg it.

08:47.680 --> 08:49.360
[Dave] He must know

08:50.040 --> 08:52.200
how much we appreciate his ability.

08:55.600 --> 08:58.240
I wouldn't say…
I just think he's fabulous.

09:00.240 --> 09:05.720
[Russell] What Dad's very good at is,
if there's somebody he wants to impress,

09:05.800 --> 09:09.040
he really can, but I don't think
he's ever wanted to impress me.

09:09.120 --> 09:11.120
There's no need to have a conversation.

09:11.640 --> 09:14.480
Do you know what I mean?
Why would you try and

09:15.040 --> 09:17.320
impress something
that used to live in your balls?

09:18.320 --> 09:20.000
That's kind of how I felt.

09:21.440 --> 09:24.800
Whereas my mom would happily
have me right back in her fanny.

09:26.920 --> 09:27.880
[Russell sniggers]

09:29.080 --> 09:32.240
[upbeat pop music plays]

09:34.400 --> 09:36.160
[Ninette] Russell thought of it first.

09:36.720 --> 09:39.000
[Russell] So I'm the oldest,
and then I've got

09:39.080 --> 09:41.600
a brother and sister
who were two years younger than me.

09:41.680 --> 09:44.880
They're twins,
and they have nothing in common.

09:45.440 --> 09:47.360
He hated these two babies because

09:47.440 --> 09:51.840
they took his little starship out.

09:51.920 --> 09:55.400
But then he got over that,
and I think he took to Daniel,

09:56.040 --> 09:57.960
because he was a boy

09:58.040 --> 09:59.560
and they did boy things together.

09:59.640 --> 10:02.600
And that was…
Kerry was always tagging along.

10:02.680 --> 10:05.480
She was always, like, the goalie.

10:06.920 --> 10:09.000
[woman] He got Daniel with the football.

10:09.080 --> 10:12.440
And so then I was...
It was just me and my mirror.

10:12.520 --> 10:13.560
[Kerry laughing]

10:13.640 --> 10:16.400
Didn't really care what Kerry was up to.

10:16.480 --> 10:19.440
All I ever wanted to do was have
a game of footie with Russ, really.

10:19.520 --> 10:24.120
If she'd been any good at footie,
then happy days. But she wasn't,

10:24.880 --> 10:26.160
so gotta fall on your sword.

10:26.240 --> 10:28.640
Nobody makes me laugh
more than my brother.

10:29.160 --> 10:30.560
Women hate him.

10:30.640 --> 10:33.480
He's really funny,
but he's not dinner-party funny.

10:34.000 --> 10:35.760
He's Wetherspoons funny.

10:35.840 --> 10:37.080
[laughter]

10:37.920 --> 10:39.480
That's me and my brother,

10:39.560 --> 10:40.440
topless.

10:40.520 --> 10:41.880
That's me with me old teeth.

10:42.840 --> 10:46.280
That's him with cheekbones,
before he turned into such a fat fuck.

10:46.360 --> 10:47.680
[bell dings]

10:48.280 --> 10:51.280
I'd certainly say
I was a useful pet for him.

10:51.360 --> 10:55.000
As in, "We could jump over that fence."

10:55.720 --> 10:58.360
"Do you want to jump over first
and see if you hurt your leg?"

10:58.440 --> 10:59.880
[man] You're live now.

11:00.760 --> 11:01.600
Hello.

11:02.120 --> 11:06.480
[Russell] So Daniel's got epilepsy,
and what's awful about it is that

11:06.560 --> 11:09.520
I know when it happened,
because we were riding our bikes

11:09.600 --> 11:13.280
down a hill, and a battery fell out of my…

11:15.400 --> 11:19.160
light on the back of my bike.
It sort of flicked.

11:19.240 --> 11:20.320
I looked around. It went…

11:20.400 --> 11:21.880
[cracking sound]
Like that.

11:21.960 --> 11:24.760
Daniel went like that over the battery.
[whooshing sound]

11:24.840 --> 11:27.840
Crack! He smacked his head,
and was on the floor.

11:28.360 --> 11:31.560
It was obviously before
the days of helmets and all this shit.

11:31.640 --> 11:33.120
I was like, "Oh God, he's dead."

11:34.560 --> 11:36.400
[man] Out the way, Russell!
Move your big head.

11:39.680 --> 11:42.480
He obviously hurt himself,
but he didn't go to hospital.

11:42.560 --> 11:45.840
No, he just went to the doctor's.
She cleaned him up, and he was fine.

11:45.920 --> 11:48.760
Know that bone
that goes all the way down there?

11:49.920 --> 11:51.440
-[man] What, the spine?
-Yeah.

11:51.520 --> 11:52.800
[man] Think it's done any damage?

11:52.880 --> 11:55.400
And then a week later,
he's upstairs with Kerry.

11:55.480 --> 11:59.000
I went into his room,
and he was staring into space.

11:59.080 --> 12:02.200
He stared through me. He wasn't there.

12:02.280 --> 12:04.320
She's like, "Russell, Russell!"

12:04.400 --> 12:06.840
I run upstairs,
and my brother's just like this.

12:11.200 --> 12:13.360
You know, and he starts fitting.

12:13.440 --> 12:15.360
It's fucking horrendous.

12:15.440 --> 12:19.360
-I was hugging him like he was gonna die.
-He was in a terrible state.

12:20.160 --> 12:21.680
So I thought this was it.

12:22.200 --> 12:26.080
After about three minutes
of watching him just go bluer and bluer,

12:26.160 --> 12:29.760
in that three minutes, I thought
I was holding my boy for the last time.

12:29.840 --> 12:32.920
Dad was crying.
It's the only time I've ever seen him cry.

12:33.000 --> 12:34.960
It was absolutely horrific.

12:35.040 --> 12:36.680
Whenever the events would happen,

12:36.760 --> 12:38.080
you weren't there.

12:38.160 --> 12:41.960
They were the victims.
They had to witness it and deal with it.

12:42.040 --> 12:45.720
All I was doing was,
you'd have the seizure, wake up, and go,

12:46.280 --> 12:47.520
"What's going on here?"

12:47.600 --> 12:50.600
It was funny,
because we were around Daniel

12:50.680 --> 12:52.720
and he was unconscious.

12:52.800 --> 12:55.120
Then he just sat up, looked at us,

12:55.200 --> 12:57.200
and he farted.

12:57.280 --> 12:59.960
[laughing] And then, it was just,
everyone was laughing.

13:00.040 --> 13:03.160
That's almost a perfect example
of the power of comedy

13:03.240 --> 13:05.560
because we were broken as a family.

13:05.640 --> 13:08.600
Like we thought we were going to lose

13:08.680 --> 13:10.040
the best of us.

13:10.120 --> 13:11.960
Daniel was the best.

13:12.040 --> 13:15.920
And he comes round
after this horrific ordeal

13:16.440 --> 13:19.480
and farts for such…

13:20.000 --> 13:21.440
It was a proper like…

13:21.520 --> 13:24.320
[squeaky sound]

13:25.640 --> 13:27.400
And everyone smiled.

13:27.920 --> 13:31.440
That's why comedy's
such an amazing tool for navigating life.

13:31.520 --> 13:36.120
If you can find laughter in pain,
you can kind of get through anything.

13:49.400 --> 13:51.840
So the pandemic happened,

13:51.920 --> 13:53.280
the tour was canceled,

13:53.360 --> 13:56.520
and I was basically sent to my room.

13:57.720 --> 14:01.640
[upbeat music playing]

14:01.720 --> 14:05.320
Hello, and welcome to my bedroom.

14:05.400 --> 14:08.520
While I was in my bedroom,
I did a TV show for Sky.

14:08.600 --> 14:12.320
The show was me doing some topical jokes,
chatting to other comedians.

14:12.400 --> 14:15.840
You're the highlight of my entire fucking…
three months it feels like I've been here.

14:17.440 --> 14:18.400
[Russell yelling]

14:20.840 --> 14:25.960
Congratulations for being the first person
to get me to put trousers on for a month.

14:26.040 --> 14:28.320
We'd get musicians
to perform from their home.

14:30.280 --> 14:32.400
♪ …We're in lockdown
Please don't cough around me ♪

14:32.480 --> 14:33.520
♪ Keep your salivas ♪

14:34.600 --> 14:37.560
And I interviewed people
who were doing amazing things.

14:38.080 --> 14:41.880
They are underpaid,
and still on the front line.

14:41.960 --> 14:45.160
I keep saying, moving forward,
when this nightmare is over,

14:45.240 --> 14:48.360
we should have a national discussion
of how we treat our working class,

14:48.440 --> 14:51.600
and how we treat people,
like the NHS staff.

14:51.680 --> 14:55.000
Obviously, my wife
is one of those amazing people,

14:55.080 --> 15:00.040
but we have a rule that
she doesn't want to be in this world.

15:00.120 --> 15:02.360
That's why she's not going to
be in this documentary.

15:03.160 --> 15:04.920
She does exist, by the way.

15:06.400 --> 15:08.960
I did talk to
one of her friends who's a doctor.

15:09.680 --> 15:11.840
That was a lot harder
than I thought it was gonna be.

15:11.920 --> 15:14.680
At the end of all of this, I don't know

15:14.760 --> 15:17.960
how many people will have lost
their lives, and been seriously affected.

15:18.720 --> 15:20.960
But I would presume that
the least somebody wants to do

15:21.040 --> 15:23.880
is be able to look back and say,
well, they did their best.

15:23.960 --> 15:26.400
Your best is following the advice.

15:27.400 --> 15:28.440
-Please do it.
-Yeah.

15:28.960 --> 15:32.520
You've actually made me
feel emotional there, because that's…

15:33.920 --> 15:36.040
That is exactly… We should fess up.

15:36.120 --> 15:38.000
You're best friends with my wife.

15:38.720 --> 15:41.920
And that's exactly what you're both doing,

15:42.000 --> 15:44.760
is that you're completely doing your best.

15:44.840 --> 15:49.200
It's quite… The thing I find typical,
watching the news,

15:49.280 --> 15:54.040
is when you see
the doctors covered in all the PPE stuff.

15:54.920 --> 15:58.520
And to think that someone you love

15:58.600 --> 16:02.600
is day in, day out,
putting themselves at risk

16:02.680 --> 16:05.920
to save others is utterly humbling.

16:06.000 --> 16:09.560
This was really early on,
when people didn't know the situation,

16:09.640 --> 16:11.400
other than the fact
that people were dying.

16:11.480 --> 16:15.000
You know, he felt like
he was needed to do something.

16:15.080 --> 16:17.800
[James] This was as close
as he could get to doing stand-up.

16:17.880 --> 16:20.880
He had so much downtime.
What was he gonna do?

16:20.960 --> 16:23.200
[Daniel] All he'd been doing
is talking to his dog.

16:23.280 --> 16:27.560
It was all right,
performing in your bedroom, but

16:28.240 --> 16:30.560
it's nothing compared to stand-up.

16:31.400 --> 16:35.280
Honestly, I was so desperate to gig again,

16:35.360 --> 16:36.600
so desperate.

16:37.280 --> 16:40.400
I'm deeply, deeply missing stand-up,

16:40.480 --> 16:42.160
so much, just…

16:43.400 --> 16:44.840
Yeah, I have a mic,

16:45.320 --> 16:49.080
that isn't even plugged in,
but even holding it, like it…

16:49.600 --> 16:52.800
It's something about
the coldness of it as well.

16:52.880 --> 16:55.920
It just sort of makes sense.
You know what I mean?

16:56.000 --> 16:57.480
