who is unlike
any human being I've ever met.

32:49.480 --> 32:52.720
-I wouldn't mind having a trim.
-Yeah? What do you want doing?

32:53.280 --> 32:54.800
[Russell laughing]

32:54.880 --> 32:59.080
-What are you doing with this?
-I'd like this just shaved, if I may.

32:59.160 --> 33:00.720
-Have you got a cutthroat?
-Yeah.

33:00.800 --> 33:02.120
-Fuck me!
-Do it all the time.

33:02.200 --> 33:03.880
-Do you? Wow.
-Do it every day.

33:03.960 --> 33:06.640
Will used to wear makeup, a pink mohawk,

33:06.720 --> 33:08.680
and loads of Care Bear tattoos.

33:08.760 --> 33:12.960
We were traveling all over the place.
We were doing a gig in Hartlepool.

33:13.040 --> 33:16.360
Somebody threw a glass at us
when we were walking in the street.

33:16.880 --> 33:20.000
We were doing a gig in Manchester,
and the bloke didn't want to pay

33:20.080 --> 33:22.200
because he thought Wil was shit.

33:22.840 --> 33:25.600
In a world that's now pretty fluid,

33:26.520 --> 33:28.960
he was absolutely fluid,

33:29.040 --> 33:31.120
in a far more rigid world.

33:31.200 --> 33:33.000
I don't know what schools you went to,

33:33.080 --> 33:35.840
but if you were a boy,
and went to my primary school aged five,

33:35.920 --> 33:40.960
and you come in with
Gloworms, Wuzzles, Popples, She-Ra,

33:41.040 --> 33:42.880
and a Bluebird A La Carte Kitchen,

33:43.960 --> 33:46.680
then you would have to learn
to fight pretty dang sharpish.

33:47.200 --> 33:49.840
How long was that we first started?
It's been nearly 20 years.

33:49.920 --> 33:50.800
Fucking, it is.

33:50.880 --> 33:54.160
We used to think people who'd been going
20 years had been going forever back then.

33:54.680 --> 33:59.200
He also once really tried
to fuck one of my aunties,

34:00.560 --> 34:05.080
because he then wanted me
to have to call him "Uncle Wil."

34:05.600 --> 34:09.000
I remember being in
John Oliver's flat in Herne Hill

34:09.080 --> 34:14.040
and playing a recording
I had of you at the Comedy Box,

34:14.720 --> 34:18.960
and John listening to that and going,
"Fucking hell, he's really good."

34:19.040 --> 34:24.000
And I wonder if that's why
he took you under his wing a bit.

34:24.080 --> 34:27.760
When you go to America,
what's amazing is, you see his face

34:27.840 --> 34:30.640
on taxis, and big huge billboards.

34:30.720 --> 34:32.320
-It's properly cool.
-Fucking mad.

34:32.400 --> 34:35.440
-Yeah. You know.
-It's John. It's fucking crazy.

34:35.520 --> 34:37.520
There are little moments

34:38.920 --> 34:42.280
when a friend of yours
does stand-up that are…

34:44.560 --> 34:46.720
really fun to witness.

34:46.800 --> 34:48.480
So watching them

34:49.640 --> 34:52.600
do early gigs and do really well,

34:52.680 --> 34:54.760
watching them do badly,
but standing their ground

34:54.840 --> 34:58.920
because they're finding their voice.
Watching their first Edinburgh show.

34:59.000 --> 35:01.280
Watching them, in Russell's case,
finding a TV show

35:01.360 --> 35:04.040
where he could fit his voice to a format.

35:04.120 --> 35:07.120
We were lucky to have each other
at that particular time.

35:07.640 --> 35:10.040
The fact he used
the phrase "golden generation"

35:10.120 --> 35:13.840
is something I will use against him
for the rest of our lives now.

35:14.560 --> 35:16.320
I'm gonna text him after this and say,

35:16.400 --> 35:19.360
"Listen. One member
of the golden generation to another,

35:19.440 --> 35:21.720
what a golden time to be alive."

35:25.440 --> 35:29.560
In the UK, we have the Edinburgh Fringe.
It's this amazing festival

35:29.640 --> 35:34.080
where, as a comic,
you can hone your craft.

35:34.160 --> 35:36.680
There's reviewers there.
There's TV people there.

35:37.200 --> 35:38.360
Everyone's there.

35:38.440 --> 35:42.880
If you take a great show to Edinburgh,
it can change your life.

35:44.000 --> 35:45.800
That's Steve Hall.

35:45.880 --> 35:47.840
I'm doing a video diary for Edinburgh.

35:47.920 --> 35:51.280
There were so many people
telling him he was the next big thing.

35:51.360 --> 35:53.160
I think it was doing his head in a bit,

35:53.240 --> 35:55.960
because he knew that he wasn't ready.

35:56.040 --> 35:59.000
I have to be very quick. Someone else
is about to go on, but this is my room.

35:59.080 --> 36:02.640
[Russell] 2006,
I figured out how to do it and

36:03.640 --> 36:05.840
I knew what I was about.

36:05.920 --> 36:08.680
Then started doing stuff on TV

36:09.200 --> 36:11.040
and it got out of hand a bit.

36:11.120 --> 36:12.880
It was crazy.

36:12.960 --> 36:16.920
We did a gig in Brighton and 1,800 people.

36:17.000 --> 36:20.680
We'd been performing in front of 400,
and suddenly 1,800 there.

36:20.760 --> 36:24.000
And the energy,
and you're just… and they're like…

36:24.080 --> 36:25.040
[cheering]

36:25.120 --> 36:27.240
Then you come off,
and it's just a bit much.

36:27.320 --> 36:30.880
We had the post-adrenaline slump.

36:30.960 --> 36:34.840
We walked around and he's going,
"This is all happening so quickly."

36:34.920 --> 36:40.520
"So can we just go and get a kebab?
Can we go and just sit?"

36:41.240 --> 36:45.040
"Sit by the beach in Brighton and go,
'Fucking hell!'"

36:45.120 --> 36:47.440
It's such a headfuck to have that kind of…

36:47.520 --> 36:50.120
[cheering]

36:50.200 --> 36:52.520
"Nothing now. Go on, go to bed."

36:53.160 --> 36:54.440
"I don't know if I can."

36:54.520 --> 36:56.520
If you're not used to it,

36:56.600 --> 37:00.760
and then a year later,
we were just doing arenas.

37:00.840 --> 37:02.840
[audience cheering]

37:06.960 --> 37:10.520
There's such a massive adrenaline buzz

37:10.600 --> 37:14.680
about going out in front of 15,000 people.

37:14.760 --> 37:18.280
They're all back there,
and all up there, and I'm thinking,

37:18.360 --> 37:21.920
"Oh my God, they've come to see my boy."

37:22.520 --> 37:24.920
It's like watching fireworks.
How does this happen?

37:25.000 --> 37:26.200
It's just brilliant.

37:26.280 --> 37:27.800
He's like a volcano.

37:27.880 --> 37:31.080
He starts off rumbling,
it builds, and it just goes…

37:31.160 --> 37:32.640
[roaring]

37:38.560 --> 37:43.280
It's crazy. Twenty years ago,
I was doing gigs to 30 people.

37:43.360 --> 37:46.680
Now I can sometimes do gigs to thousands.

37:47.800 --> 37:50.040
It's mental to experience that.

37:50.840 --> 37:53.000
Now we're in a situation where you think,

37:53.080 --> 37:56.560
"God, will I ever get
to experience that again?"

38:07.400 --> 38:09.560
You look at it and go, "Is this allowed?"

38:09.640 --> 38:12.560
They're not wearing masks,
but it is allowed. It's fine.

38:13.120 --> 38:15.200
But it's just…

38:16.840 --> 38:18.480
I don't know. It's weird now.

38:19.160 --> 38:21.920
Maybe today,
with the Bond film being canceled.

38:22.000 --> 38:23.360
[Russell] Did you see the cinemas?

38:23.440 --> 38:26.520
-Cineworld are closed. 12,000 jobs.
-Fuck, they're broke.

38:27.840 --> 38:29.640
135 cinemas closed.

38:29.720 --> 38:33.560
It's a bizarre thing.
You'd never have called it a year ago.

38:34.120 --> 38:36.240
You are better
for Britain than James Bond.

38:36.320 --> 38:38.400
I am better for Britain, exactly.

38:38.480 --> 38:40.160
[laughing]

38:40.240 --> 38:43.200
The venue were on their arse.
They had no money.

38:43.280 --> 38:47.040
They were struggling
to have enough money to pay the rent

38:47.640 --> 38:49.240
that week, I believe.

38:49.320 --> 38:54.600
So I think Russell donated
all of his side of things

38:54.680 --> 38:58.680
to the venue
to help them, you know, survive.

38:59.360 --> 39:04.920
Ladies and gentlemen of the Clapham Grand!

39:05.000 --> 39:07.680
[cheering]

39:07.760 --> 39:12.320
Are you ready?

39:12.400 --> 39:13.480
[cheering]

39:13.560 --> 39:15.640
[Russell]
We were getting tested before every gig,

39:15.720 --> 39:18.760
and the audience were socially distanced,

39:18.840 --> 39:23.320
although they'd set it up
so it felt like the crowd was full.

39:23.400 --> 39:26.080
It felt like
we were the only show in town.

39:26.160 --> 39:32.920
Mr. Russell Howard!

39:33.960 --> 39:35.040
Look at you all.

39:37.000 --> 39:38.200
In your bubbles.

39:40.120 --> 39:42.280
It became this really cool gig where

39:42.360 --> 39:44.760
I could try new material,
I'd invite other comics

39:44.840 --> 39:46.840
to come down and try new stuff.

39:46.920 --> 39:51.200
One week, I even invited James Bay,
who's a mate of mine.

39:51.280 --> 39:55.360
He'd normally be performing to thousands.

39:55.440 --> 39:58.640
He hadn't done a gig
in like a year at this stage.

39:58.720 --> 39:59.760
It was so cool.

39:59.840 --> 40:02.680
I almost don't know how to feel.
I'm like, "A gig?"

40:03.320 --> 40:08.440
[Russell] But the difference is,
how many new songs are you doing?

40:08.520 --> 40:09.360
I'm gonna do one.

40:09.440 --> 40:13.200
I did the equivalent of 15 new songs,

40:13.760 --> 40:16.720
three of which,
it turns out, were actually good songs.

40:16.800 --> 40:18.040
[laughing]

40:18.120 --> 40:20.360
The rest were, "What do you think…"

40:21.800 --> 40:27.280
Please welcome to the stage,
the magnificent James Bay!

40:27.360 --> 40:29.880
[cheering and applause]

40:44.000 --> 40:48.360
I forgot, I've got an important piece
of housekeeping. I'm so sorry, James.

40:48.880 --> 40:52.160
Under the current guidelines,
you're not allowed to sing along.

40:52.240 --> 40:54.360
I can't fucking believe
I forgot to tell you this.

40:54.440 --> 40:57.440
So enjoy it. Clap, cheer, fucking go mad.

40:57.520 --> 40:59.800
But don't sing, because that's very bad.

40:59.880 --> 41:02.880
I'd never gigged with a musician before.

41:02.960 --> 41:07.160
And it was really cool,
because backstage, you could sort of

41:07.840 --> 41:10.280
see that we're all fundamentally the same.

41:10.360 --> 41:12.160
[Russell] It's almost back to open mic.

41:12.240 --> 41:14.680
-Oh that--
-In a sense. Do you know what I mean?

41:14.760 --> 41:17.400
Coming here tonight,
I was getting all the open-mic feels

41:17.480 --> 41:19.600
in the way that you understand them.

41:19.680 --> 41:23.200
There's no glamorizing this moment
when I've got to tune the guitar.

41:23.280 --> 41:24.640
[laughter]

41:24.720 --> 41:27.400
[Russell] Is this the new song, James?
It's pretty experimental.

41:27.480 --> 41:29.160
[laughter]

41:31.080 --> 41:32.040
Are we in tune?

41:33.720 --> 41:35.520
-Fill in, would you?
-[Russell] Yep.

41:36.520 --> 41:38.520
♪ If you're happy and you… ♪

41:38.600 --> 41:39.640
[laughter]

41:39.720 --> 41:41.200
I remember he started saying,

41:41.280 --> 41:44.520
"I'm going to do some gigs again."
It was during the times where

41:44.600 --> 41:47.200
some people in the UK

41:47.280 --> 41:49.680
were all a bit nervous
about this and that.

41:49.760 --> 41:50.840
You knew with Russ,

41:50.920 --> 41:56.600
he was going to find a way,
in a non-wanky way, to help,

41:57.120 --> 42:01.520
and the only way he can help is by
offering his jokes out to people.

42:01.600 --> 42:05.200
We're used to being out,
and working, and gigging.

42:05.720 --> 42:08.480
To have all of that
taken away from you was

42:09.280 --> 42:11.400
mind-bendingly bleak.

42:12.040 --> 42:14.680
My mental health in this whole pandemic

42:14.760 --> 42:17.800
has been assisted massively by

42:18.640 --> 42:20.200
these Clapham gigs.

42:20.800 --> 42:22.000
And they were joyous.

42:24.960 --> 42:27.240
[Russell] The gigs were fun,
but the more it went on,

42:27.320 --> 42:30.560
it became evident that
we were hitting a second wave of COVID.

42:31.680 --> 42:33.880
Do you think
this is gonna be the last one?

42:34.720 --> 42:37.680
What's the moral compass on this?
It's difficult to tell, isn't it?

42:37.760 --> 42:39.920
No, I think, you know.

42:40.560 --> 42:43.680
If we're legally allowed to do it,
we're obliged to do it, I think.

42:43.760 --> 42:44.600
Yeah.

42:44.680 --> 42:48.600
Boris said yesterday that in two weeks,
there's going to be deaths.

42:48.680 --> 42:50.960
-So if they're sort of talking like that…
-Yeah.

42:52.120 --> 42:56.080
[man] Is your intention to keep
doing this, if you can, the Sunday gig?

42:56.160 --> 42:58.400
We're going to do this
until the wheels come off.

42:58.480 --> 43:00.480
-That's generally--
-Yeah.

43:00.560 --> 43:02.360
Around this time, we were like,

43:02.440 --> 43:06.840
"The tour dates
in early 2021 aren't gonna happen."

43:06.920 --> 43:09.040
We were trying
to figure out what could we do.

43:09.120 --> 43:10.760
What's plan A? What's plan B?

43:10.840 --> 43:16.320
Because obviously, I want to do the gigs,
but you have to keep people safe.

43:16.840 --> 43:20.640
You know, if there comes a point
where you can't do both, you have to stop.

43:21.200 --> 43:26.720
But we did have some shows
in New Zealand that were already booked.

43:27.840 --> 43:33.160
There's talk, very early talk,
of possibly doing the gigs in New Zealand.

43:33.240 --> 43:38.880
What we would have to do
is quarantine in a hotel for two weeks.

43:38.960 --> 43:41.240
I think I could do two weeks in a hotel,

43:41.320 --> 43:44.360
knowing that I then had a month of gigs.

43:44.440 --> 43:47.360
New Zealand had obviously done
a different approach to COVID.

43:47.440 --> 43:48.880
They'd locked down early.

43:48.960 --> 43:51.200
They'd eradicated it. It wasn't there.

43:51.280 --> 43:54.280
There was a chance,
if you appealed to the government,

43:54.360 --> 43:55.720
that they would let you in,

43:55.800 --> 43:58.840
so we could do the gigs
that we already had sold out.

43:58.920 --> 44:03.520
[Russell] That's what happens
if you have a competent leader in charge

44:03.600 --> 44:07.640
of your country. As opposed to a man
who is part alpaca, part thesaurus.

44:09.960 --> 44:16.160
Good evening, and apologies for disturbing
Saturday evening with more news of COVID.

44:16.240 --> 44:21.360
[Johnson] Non-essential shops, leisure,
and entertainment venues will be closed.

44:21.920 --> 44:25.240
Pubs, bars, restaurants must close.

44:25.320 --> 44:28.240
It goes without saying, everybody,
don't forget the basics.

44:28.320 --> 44:33.480
Hands, face, space.
Get a test if you have symptoms.

44:33.560 --> 44:35.960
Thank you very much. Stay safe. Thank you.

44:37.480 --> 44:39.280
[Russell] So the gigs ended.

44:39.840 --> 44:42.160
We were back in lockdown again.

44:42.240 --> 44:44.840
In New Zealand,
there was a glimmer of hope.

44:45.680 --> 44:48.600
So we wrote to New Zealand,

44:48.680 --> 44:51.800
and they wrote back,
saying that we were allowed to go.

44:52.720 --> 44:54.320
See ya.

44:54.400 --> 44:55.560
Right, see you later.

45:03.720 --> 45:07.160
It's my solemn wish
that I don't die before you get back.

45:09.480 --> 45:11.000
All right. See you later.

45:19.520 --> 45:22.320
I've just got here, and literally

45:23.120 --> 45:26.160
the UK's gone into
the worst lockdown since March.

45:26.240 --> 45:30.120
So I feel really guilty, if I'm honest.

45:31.720 --> 45:36.760
And on the bus journey here,
seeing it so green, sunny, and beautiful,

45:36.840 --> 45:38.280
I felt terrible.

45:39.560 --> 45:42.400
Now I'm going to be
in a room for two weeks,

45:42.480 --> 45:43.880
I don't feel so bad.

45:43.960 --> 45:46.240
The second wave
was ripping through the UK.

45:46.320 --> 45:50.200
My wife is working on a COVID ward,

45:50.280 --> 45:54.720
and I'm in a hotel room
in New Zealand for two weeks,

45:55.320 --> 45:57.320
just so I can go and do stand-up.

45:57.400 --> 45:59.880
Me and my tour manager Kumar

45:59.960 --> 46:03.000
just spent an hour
in the car park walking in a circle.

46:03.560 --> 46:05.800
A year ago, if I had rang him up and gone,

46:05.880 --> 46:11.480
"Hey mate. Yeah, do you fancy walking
in a circle for an hour in the car park?"

46:12.840 --> 46:15.200
I very much doubt he'd have come. And yet,

46:15.280 --> 46:18.920
we've just had
a really lovely walk in a car park.

46:19.000 --> 46:23.800
It's really strange, isn't it?
When everything is taken from you,

46:25.040 --> 46:27.160
how little things are exciting.

46:27.240 --> 46:31.320
I don't know anybody that would've gone
all the way to New Zealand

46:31.400 --> 46:34.640
and agreed to quarantine for two weeks

46:35.360 --> 46:37.280
to do three shows.

46:37.360 --> 46:39.160
I mean, who would do that?

46:39.240 --> 46:40.560
I tried to stay active.

46:41.600 --> 46:44.680
As active as you can
in a three-by-three meter room.

46:44.760 --> 46:48.280
Had to drag that through the lobby.
Hey, do you want to look like a cunt?

46:48.360 --> 46:51.280
Drag a bike
through a lobby in a quarantine hotel.

46:52.320 --> 46:53.640
I was pretty productive.

46:53.720 --> 46:55.760
I did a lot of writing.

46:55.840 --> 46:57.320
Went on the bike once.

46:58.600 --> 47:00.480
I'm not gonna say I didn't let myself go.

47:02.680 --> 47:04.120
I'm quite messy.

47:06.640 --> 47:09.000
This is the old… That's the masks.

47:10.840 --> 47:13.200
That's the room. As you can see,

47:14.680 --> 47:16.000
it's a bit of a state.

47:16.720 --> 47:19.400
There's something about isolation that

47:19.480 --> 47:24.480
sort of makes you reflect on
the magnitude of what we're going through.

47:25.160 --> 47:30.120
I'm allowed to be sat
in a hotel room in my own filth,

47:30.200 --> 47:33.640
while there's nurses,
doctors, and key workers

47:33.720 --> 47:37.080
who are working their balls off
to make people safe.

47:37.160 --> 47:41.400
It's a humbling experience
to realize how lucky you are.

47:42.320 --> 47:46.440
Christ, what must it be like
to be a doctor or a nurse…

47:50.640 --> 47:51.800
during a pandemic?

47:54.640 --> 47:59.240
Just keep going.
Just keep going. Just keep going.

48:00.560 --> 48:01.720
Fucking mad, man.

48:06.040 --> 48:08.840
There's such a base level of sadness

48:08.920 --> 48:12.120
in the world at the minute,
because of everything that's going on.

48:12.680 --> 48:14.520
And it's your job

48:15.120 --> 48:16.440
as a comedian

48:17.360 --> 48:19.640
to A, not succumb to that,

48:20.240 --> 48:22.120
and sink into the sadness.

48:22.920 --> 48:24.840
And B,

48:24.920 --> 48:26.320
rise above it,

48:26.960 --> 48:30.040
and lift people out of the sadness.

48:30.120 --> 48:33.760
It's lofty. It's wanky. It's pretentious.

48:33.840 --> 48:35.800
But at its best,

48:37.120 --> 48:41.160
that's what stand-up does.
That's what it does to me, anyway.

48:41.240 --> 48:46.520
When I watch Billy Connolly,
or Dave Chappelle, or Bill Burr,

48:47.680 --> 48:51.680
or Taylor Tomlinson,
or Seinfeld, or Lee Evans,

48:52.640 --> 48:53.800
or Frank Skinner.

49:00.040 --> 49:02.000
To just fucking laugh.

49:03.400 --> 49:05.080
What? No, you're rambling.

49:07.160 --> 49:09.280
I was one day away from freedom.

49:09.360 --> 49:11.160
And I was so excited.

49:11.240 --> 49:13.480
Do you know what
I've been doing the whole time?

49:13.560 --> 49:14.680
Just writing jokes.

49:18.720 --> 49:20.520
Fuck, I'm looking forward to these gigs.

49:20.600 --> 49:22.080
[clicking teeth]

49:22.160 --> 49:25.760
In a country totally free from COVID.

49:25.840 --> 49:28.440
No masks, no social distancing,
and they were like,

49:28.520 --> 49:30.160
"You should go out. Enjoy it."

49:30.720 --> 49:33.120
"Go to the beach. Enjoy the countryside."

49:33.200 --> 49:35.000
I was like, "Nah, let's do a gig."

49:35.800 --> 49:38.000
[man] All the way from England,

49:38.080 --> 49:42.200
Mr. Russell Howard!

49:42.280 --> 49:45.000
[cheering and applause]

49:51.360 --> 49:52.280
Yes.

49:53.120 --> 49:55.040
Yes. Yes.

49:56.400 --> 49:57.640
Yes.

50:00.560 --> 50:01.640
Wow. Thank you.

50:05.600 --> 50:06.560
Kia ora.

50:06.640 --> 50:07.960
[laughter]

50:08.040 --> 50:13.040
We quickly realized
that if we got back to England,

50:13.120 --> 50:16.320
we wouldn't be
able to do anything in England at all.

50:16.400 --> 50:18.880
'Cause everything was closed
and locked down.

50:19.480 --> 50:22.560
But we started thinking,
"You know, while we're here,

50:22.640 --> 50:26.680
rather than going home,
and doing nothing at home,

50:26.760 --> 50:30.640
I wonder what would happen if we just
put another couple of shows on?"

50:30.720 --> 50:33.360
Originally, we'd only sold three gigs,

50:34.320 --> 50:36.400
but we just kept adding more gigs.

50:36.480 --> 50:38.200
We just kept going and going.

50:39.200 --> 50:42.520
In the end, we ended up doing 17 shows,

50:43.200 --> 50:46.280
and we ended up staying
for like six weeks?

50:46.360 --> 50:49.680
[Russell] It was so amazing.
Like, you know, full crowds,

50:49.760 --> 50:51.520
no social distancing, no masks.

50:51.600 --> 50:54.280
Doing these huge shows was

50:54.360 --> 50:56.120
absolutely insane.

50:56.760 --> 51:00.400
But it was still on a knife-edge,
because if one person gets COVID

51:00.480 --> 51:02.520
in New Zealand,
they shut down immediately.

51:02.600 --> 51:05.800
There was one gig
in Auckland in particular

51:05.880 --> 51:07.600
that was really close.

51:07.680 --> 51:11.960
[woman] A little change
in circumstance today.

51:12.040 --> 51:16.280
Well, a big change in circumstance today,
as a result of the some of the news

51:16.360 --> 51:21.320
that we've received
around some positive test results.

51:21.400 --> 51:23.440
for COVID-19 in Auckland.

51:23.520 --> 51:26.120
That's why we've taken
this cautious approach

51:26.200 --> 51:30.440
of asking Aucklanders
to move into level 3.

51:31.120 --> 51:33.520
So for the next 72 hours,

51:33.600 --> 51:35.960
if you're in Auckland, please stay home.

51:36.040 --> 51:37.560
We were doing two shows.

51:37.640 --> 51:41.360
The first show,
he was on stage. Everything's fine.

51:41.440 --> 51:43.840
During his performance,

51:43.920 --> 51:46.480
everybody's phone started twitching.

51:46.560 --> 51:50.680
It said everybody has to be indoors

51:50.760 --> 51:52.000
by twelve o'clock.

51:53.120 --> 51:56.040
There is a full lockdown. This is serious.

51:57.160 --> 51:58.840
[Russell] I had no idea it was happening.

51:58.920 --> 52:02.440
It was only when I came offstage
that I realized what had gone on.

52:02.520 --> 52:06.160
Everyone was wearing a mask.
Everyone's standing away from me.

52:06.240 --> 52:09.640
It freaked him out.
He was like, "What's going on?"

52:09.720 --> 52:12.280
The second show had a different energy.

52:12.360 --> 52:14.440
-Feels weird, don't it?
-[nervous laughter]

52:14.520 --> 52:16.640
Feels all strange all of a sudden.

52:16.720 --> 52:19.480
We did a show an hour ago,
and everyone's like, "Wahey!"

52:19.560 --> 52:21.520
Then they left and they're like, "Oh no."

52:21.600 --> 52:23.360
[laughter]

52:24.760 --> 52:26.880
And now I've got to make you laugh,

52:28.360 --> 52:30.480
starting the show at, "Oh no."

52:30.560 --> 52:32.400
[laughter]

52:37.040 --> 52:39.120
You're going to handle it.
It's what you do.

52:39.200 --> 52:40.840
It's phenomenal, innit?

52:40.920 --> 52:43.640
Like, there's three cases.
Jacinda is on it.

52:44.640 --> 52:46.840
She knows where they are.
They're fucking there.

52:46.920 --> 52:50.440
He's gone there. She's done that.
Boris doesn't know how many kids he's got.

52:50.520 --> 52:52.480
[laughter]

52:52.560 --> 52:55.160
[applause]

52:57.400 --> 53:02.440
It was a crazy experience.
It's like I went from performing in 2021

53:02.520 --> 53:03.800
to 2019,

53:03.880 --> 53:07.720
to 2019 to 2021 in the blink of an eye.

53:07.800 --> 53:12.240
It was like the worst kind
of time travel, in every sense.

53:12.320 --> 53:14.960
So we were having this amazing time,

53:15.040 --> 53:19.080
but you know it's temporary,
because, you know,

53:19.160 --> 53:22.280
we're heading back to the UK,
and it's going to be very different.

53:25.360 --> 53:26.840
We're now traveling

53:26.920 --> 53:30.080
on a one-way road to freedom.

53:30.160 --> 53:33.360
From the 21st of June,
we will go to step 4,

53:33.440 --> 53:37.080
and say goodbye
to most remaining restrictions.

53:37.160 --> 53:39.160
There is light ahead.

53:39.240 --> 53:41.120
So Boris did this big announcement

53:41.760 --> 53:44.600
that on June the 21st, we would be out.

53:45.120 --> 53:46.640
We would be free.

53:46.720 --> 53:51.360
It meant that the first gigs
I would do in this new freedom

53:51.440 --> 53:53.520
would be a week of gigs in Bristol

53:53.600 --> 53:58.040
in a place called the Hippodrome,
2,000-seater theater.

53:59.840 --> 54:03.160
Couldn't be better.
Literally the perfect gig

54:03.240 --> 54:07.280
at the best of times,
but after a year of people being inside,

54:07.360 --> 54:10.400
it was going to be like,
"This is going to go off!"

54:11.080 --> 54:12.720
That's what I was aiming to.

54:12.800 --> 54:16.400
But then the closer we get to June 1st,
it becomes apparent.

54:16.480 --> 54:19.200
Obviously, we're not going
to lift restrictions.

54:19.920 --> 54:21.960
I think it is sensible

54:22.040 --> 54:24.400
to wait just a little longer.

54:25.040 --> 54:26.360
So now we've got a problem.

54:26.920 --> 54:28.640
We would have had
to do something ridiculous,

54:28.720 --> 54:31.520
like 21 gigs at the Hippodrome,

54:31.600 --> 54:34.320
to fulfill all the ticket holders

54:34.960 --> 54:39.040
that bought tickets for the Hippodrome
because of the social distancing rules.

54:39.120 --> 54:41.040
And that's clearly impossible.

54:41.120 --> 54:43.880
I mean, how can you do 21 shows

54:43.960 --> 54:46.160
in the space of six days?

54:46.240 --> 54:51.520
We either had to move everything,
or cancel it.

54:51.600 --> 54:55.280
And that is when I had the idea.

54:56.520 --> 54:58.920
Why don't we do
the gigs in a football stadium?

55:02.000 --> 55:04.040
So we're doing Ashton Gate.

55:04.560 --> 55:07.160
We're going to have 2,000 people

55:07.240 --> 55:10.360
in a 10,000-seater stand.

55:12.000 --> 55:13.720
We're not allowed on the pitch.

55:13.800 --> 55:16.640
And we have to bring in our own stage,

55:16.720 --> 55:19.640
and our own sound and our own lighting.

55:19.720 --> 55:23.320
We have to make this happen in four days.

55:23.400 --> 55:25.760
So hopefully,

55:26.520 --> 55:31.200
the ambition of it creates
its own atmosphere, I hope.

55:31.280 --> 55:35.240
I think people
are so desperate to do stuff

55:35.320 --> 55:38.000
that I think they'll put up with it.
I hope they do.

55:38.080 --> 55:40.040
Hopefully we can make it look good.

55:40.600 --> 55:42.000
It's all down to Kumar.

55:42.960 --> 55:44.160
It's not. It's down to me.

55:47.080 --> 55:49.880
I sat down with Russ.
"How are we going to do this?"

55:50.680 --> 55:52.400
But it was really exciting,

55:52.480 --> 55:58.040
because we'd all rather
be doing this than not doing it.

56:02.960 --> 56:06.520
Are you here to see Russell Howard,
or for the vaccination center?

56:14.320 --> 56:20.480
♪ We used to walk down by the river ♪

56:20.560 --> 56:22.040
-[clicking fingers]
-[Russell laughing]

56:22.120 --> 56:23.520
♪ We… ♪

56:23.600 --> 56:25.960
[Kumar]
I don't think any of my other clients,

56:26.040 --> 56:29.360
or any other bands or artists,

56:29.440 --> 56:32.120
or comedians I work with would do this,

56:32.200 --> 56:34.560
'cause it makes absolutely no sense.

56:34.640 --> 56:36.800
Doesn't make sense financially.

56:36.880 --> 56:39.680
I mean, logistically, it makes no sense.

56:39.760 --> 56:41.120
My reaction was both

56:41.720 --> 56:42.880
"That's impossible,

56:43.600 --> 56:47.480
but that's brilliant."
And we tried to carry it off.

56:48.560 --> 56:49.640
[Kumar sighing]

56:49.720 --> 56:53.440
Yeah, I honestly don't know
how we're doing this.

56:55.160 --> 56:56.920
-I do.
-How?

56:57.840 --> 57:01.640
Because it's the spirit

57:01.720 --> 57:03.680
of wanting to do gigs.

57:04.200 --> 57:06.640
-[Kumar] Goddamn it, yeah.
-I think that's the thing.

57:06.720 --> 57:09.280
It's like when we were in New Zealand,

57:09.360 --> 57:12.120
and we plotted that tour,
because what else are you gonna do?

57:12.200 --> 57:13.040
[Kumar] Yeah.

57:13.120 --> 57:14.800
It doesn't matter
how many people are there.

57:14.880 --> 57:18.960
It doesn't matter
how desperately silly it looks,

57:19.040 --> 57:20.960
and it doesn't matter how

57:22.080 --> 57:25.040
convoluted the processes
of making it happen.

57:25.120 --> 57:29.280
You're determined to do it,
and that in itself is amazing.

57:29.360 --> 57:32.080
As you always say,
"Hit the stage, smile, and nut."

57:32.160 --> 57:35.200
Exactly right. Exactly right!

57:36.240 --> 57:38.480
It's raining, it's the summer,

57:38.560 --> 57:41.200
and we're doing a gig
in a stadium in Bristol.

57:42.040 --> 57:45.840
Doesn't get better than that.
It's going to be amazing. I think. I hope.

57:45.920 --> 57:47.520
Will it? Is it all right?

57:47.600 --> 57:49.080
[Kumar laughing]

57:49.160 --> 57:52.800
[guitar music playing]

57:59.200 --> 58:02.520
With the world as it is,
you've got to make the gig happen.

58:02.600 --> 58:04.520
You can't let the gig come to you.

58:05.440 --> 58:06.840
Because of social distance,

58:06.920 --> 58:10.880
we could only have
2,000 people in a 10,000 stand

58:11.520 --> 58:14.160
in a 27,000-seater stadium.

58:14.720 --> 58:17.640
Two years ago, that would have been awful.

58:18.320 --> 58:19.760
I'd have been moaning.

58:19.840 --> 58:21.960
There would have been no way to do it.

58:22.040 --> 58:24.960
But now, this feels like a triumph.

58:26.200 --> 58:31.440
People are pleased to see you.
You're ridiculously pleased to see them.

58:31.520 --> 58:33.000
You need the people.

58:33.720 --> 58:36.560
It almost felt like the past 18 months

58:36.640 --> 58:40.200
had led up to this big gig.

58:40.280 --> 58:43.280
[guitar music continues]

58:47.920 --> 58:51.080
[Kumar] Ladies and gentlemen,

58:51.160 --> 58:55.520
welcome to Ashton Gate Stadium!

58:55.600 --> 58:59.000
Are you ready?

58:59.080 --> 59:01.320
-[cheering]
-[Kumar coughing]

59:01.400 --> 59:04.040
[laughing]

59:10.280 --> 59:13.360
Please welcome to the stage,

59:13.440 --> 59:18.280
Mr. Russell Howard!

59:18.360 --> 59:21.960
[cheering and applause]

59:24.360 --> 59:25.360
Oh mate.

59:28.240 --> 59:30.280
He did just swallow his chewing gum.

59:30.360 --> 59:31.840
[laughter]

59:31.920 --> 59:33.600
Fucking hell, that was funny.

59:33.680 --> 59:36.560
[Russell] We put these shows
on sale two years ago,

59:36.640 --> 59:37.960
and there's still people there.

59:38.040 --> 59:41.240
Like, this gig
has been rearranged more times than

59:41.320 --> 59:43.280
my dad wearing leggings.

59:44.200 --> 59:46.080
You can never assume

59:46.160 --> 59:49.160
there's going to be excitement,
or people there.

59:49.240 --> 59:51.920
But when there is, it's crazy.

59:52.000 --> 59:55.480
We have done things
that you would never ordinarily do

59:55.560 --> 59:58.320
during this pandemic in order to do a gig.

59:58.400 --> 1:00:01.320
[Kumar] I think we are doing this

1:00:02.440 --> 1:00:04.120
gig at Ashton Gate Stadium

1:00:05.160 --> 1:00:07.120
because of Russell's

1:00:07.200 --> 1:00:10.680
absolute obsession with his art,

1:00:10.760 --> 1:00:12.240
and his show,

1:00:12.320 --> 1:00:17.840
and his drive to do
what he said he's going to do.

1:00:17.920 --> 1:00:21.840
I have a feeling that
the obsession will absolutely keep going.

1:00:22.480 --> 1:00:25.520
I suppose, you know,
in the same way an elite footballer,

1:00:25.600 --> 1:00:27.680
if they didn't treat it as an obsession,

1:00:27.760 --> 1:00:32.040
they wouldn't get to where
they ultimately have ended up to be.

1:00:32.120 --> 1:00:35.640
Fundamentally, I think
he's going to be like Billy Connolly.

1:00:35.720 --> 1:00:37.280
Maybe more like Ken Dodd.

1:00:37.360 --> 1:00:41.240
He will lock everyone in,
and stay on stage for like four hours

1:00:41.320 --> 1:00:42.640
like a mad bastard.

1:00:43.240 --> 1:00:45.760
I genuinely think
he's going to go like that

1:00:46.440 --> 1:00:48.200
probably until he's 80.

1:00:48.280 --> 1:00:50.320
Will he ever stop? Probably not.

1:00:50.400 --> 1:00:52.360
He'll have a gag in his coffin somewhere.

1:00:52.440 --> 1:00:53.280
[laughing]

1:01:02.960 --> 1:01:05.160
[man] Now what do you think
your documentary was about?

1:01:06.000 --> 1:01:07.840
[Russell]
I'll let you in on a little secret.

1:01:08.400 --> 1:01:11.240
I thought basically
it was going to be me saying,

1:01:11.320 --> 1:01:13.480
"Right, I've done this for 20 years."

1:01:14.240 --> 1:01:15.200
"I'm done."

1:01:15.280 --> 1:01:20.680
That's what I thought at the beginning.
Let's have a little 20-year memento

1:01:21.200 --> 1:01:23.080
and I'll kind of wander off.

1:01:23.600 --> 1:01:26.280
The problem is,
comedy is better than real life.

1:01:26.800 --> 1:01:28.600
And that is not sustainable,

1:01:29.200 --> 1:01:32.200
because it's quite hard to

1:01:33.880 --> 1:01:37.360
judge your self-esteem
through the approval of strangers.

1:01:39.640 --> 1:01:42.840
As a 40-year-old man,
this is not the best way to live.

1:01:43.920 --> 1:01:49.560
But it was such
a mindfuck of an 18 months.

1:01:49.640 --> 1:01:52.880
So within all this,
you realize, what are your options?

1:01:52.960 --> 1:01:57.520
Your options are to try
and find something to aim for,

1:01:57.600 --> 1:02:01.120
because this time will end,
and if you're lucky,

1:02:01.200 --> 1:02:03.600
and you know what it is,
and mine is, "Right."

1:02:03.680 --> 1:02:05.720
"I want to do live stand-up again."

1:02:06.320 --> 1:02:09.160
That's it. I put all my energy into that.

1:02:09.240 --> 1:02:11.640
And oddly, that's what got me through.

1:02:11.720 --> 1:02:14.240
It was writing and thinking and

1:02:15.400 --> 1:02:17.840
obsessing over stand-up,

1:02:17.920 --> 1:02:23.480
and you realize, that's probably
what you're meant to do with your life,

1:02:24.640 --> 1:02:28.480
is be a bit of a respite,
a bit of a silly kind of flame.

1:02:28.560 --> 1:02:31.080
That can come along and just dick about,

1:02:31.160 --> 1:02:36.280
and people can get drunk and laugh,
and forget about the past 18 months.

1:02:36.360 --> 1:02:40.040
Or laugh at the past 18 months,
or laugh at the absurdity of our world,

1:02:40.120 --> 1:02:43.000
because you might have lost a loved one.

1:02:43.640 --> 1:02:46.600
You might have lost a job.
You might have lost your house.

1:02:46.680 --> 1:02:50.760
You might have mentally
found this utterly draining.

1:02:57.840 --> 1:03:01.800
I'm sure if you asked anyone
to rewind back to 2019,

1:03:01.880 --> 1:03:04.280
before any of this happened,
of course they would.

1:03:04.360 --> 1:03:10.200
It has been
the most wildly unique time of our lives.

1:03:10.280 --> 1:03:14.120
We almost felt we were immune
from these kind of emergencies.

1:03:14.200 --> 1:03:17.520
These kind of disasters.
And it happened to all of us.

1:03:19.680 --> 1:03:23.160
Obviously, what's happened
has been horrific.

1:03:23.240 --> 1:03:25.800
It's been 18 months of toil,

1:03:27.240 --> 1:03:29.040
and heartache and inertia

1:03:29.680 --> 1:03:31.080
for the world.

1:03:32.360 --> 1:03:35.320
But there is always a positive.

1:03:35.400 --> 1:03:36.600
I think we're about

1:03:36.680 --> 1:03:40.560
to head into
a golden age of entertainment.

1:03:40.640 --> 1:03:45.040
I think there will be young bands
that have been sat in their houses,

1:03:45.120 --> 1:03:46.520
learning, playing.

1:03:46.600 --> 1:03:50.720
There will be filmmakers
that have watched every film and grown.

1:03:50.800 --> 1:03:52.200
There will be comedians.

1:03:52.280 --> 1:03:53.720
So much will come out.

1:03:53.800 --> 1:03:55.960
And it's going to be so exciting,

1:03:56.040 --> 1:04:00.160
because the crowds are going to be
wildly looking forward to it.

1:04:00.240 --> 1:04:02.800
People always loved live stuff.

1:04:02.880 --> 1:04:04.040
Now they've realized

1:04:04.120 --> 1:04:07.880
how much they need it,
and how much it gives you.

1:04:08.960 --> 1:04:11.440
That's what comedy can do in the moment.

1:04:11.520 --> 1:04:14.880
All those minutes and hours
and days and weeks

1:04:14.960 --> 1:04:16.880
of you, sat there thinking,

1:04:17.560 --> 1:04:19.760
pontificating about these little ideas.

1:04:19.840 --> 1:04:23.320
Suddenly, when you're
in a car park, or a lay-by,

1:04:23.400 --> 1:04:25.440
or a woods, wherever you may be,

1:04:25.520 --> 1:04:28.760
you're suddenly alive again,
and there's people there.

1:04:28.840 --> 1:04:31.920
You can hear their laughter,
and it's so human.

1:04:32.000 --> 1:04:34.320
They're all together, and it's this mass,

1:04:34.400 --> 1:04:37.320
because there is freedom in giggles.

1:04:37.400 --> 1:04:39.200
There's liberation in laughter.

1:04:39.720 --> 1:04:43.480
It's always seen as, "Comedy's silly."
But being silly is really important.

1:04:43.560 --> 1:04:46.520
If you're silly,
you can provide real moments for people.

1:04:46.600 --> 1:04:48.760
I know that sounds
really stupid, but you can.

1:04:48.840 --> 1:04:51.040
That's what comedy can do in the moment.

1:04:51.120 --> 1:04:52.960
You're presenting people
with an hour and a half

1:04:53.040 --> 1:04:56.440
of silliness, and magic,
and wonder, and absurdity.

1:04:56.520 --> 1:04:58.120
It's the fucking best.

1:05:03.600 --> 1:05:04.960
The world has been

1:05:06.440 --> 1:05:07.880
flipped upside down.

1:05:07.960 --> 1:05:09.960
We've all been in the Upside Down.

1:05:10.040 --> 1:05:12.320
It's a thing that
we never thought could happen.

1:05:12.400 --> 1:05:14.640
We're still not through it, but

1:05:15.760 --> 1:05:19.760
what option do I, a comedian, have,

1:05:19.840 --> 1:05:22.440
but to try and laugh in the face of it?

1:05:22.520 --> 1:05:23.840
So that's what I've done.

1:05:24.520 --> 1:05:26.920
[rock music playing]
